<br>
Listening to the wise words of his daughter, Athena, Zeus could not help but to beam with fatherly pride.  He quickly moved to greet Gaia as it was not in his nature to be disrespectful of the others.  He was a fair and just god and as such to disregard the greeting of one he held in such high esteem would be unheard of.  He greeted Gaia with a kiss up on the back of her hand.  &quot;As always it is a pleasure to see you, great goddess.&quot;  It was not long before the furies arrived in all the glory.  With a smile upon his lips, he greeted each of them equally and in turn.  &quot;What a pleasant surprise!  Surely these are the most glorious in all of the known world.&quot;  He poured on the charm as he greeted them.<br>
<br>
Zeus waited to speak with Athena as she handled her invisible guest.  He chuckled wondering why it was that a god such as Hypnos would appear invisible when most of those gathered had the power to discern his presence and would surely question his motives for not revealing himself. <br>
